  "why": "The method proposed in the paper, SneakyPrompt, generates adversarial inputs directly in their final, serialized format. The inputs to the target text-to-image models are text prompts, which are discrete sequences of tokens. SneakyPrompt operates by replacing sensitive tokens within a prompt with other tokens from a vocabulary. The resulting adversarial prompt is a new text string. This generated text is inherently stable and not susceptible to alteration or loss of perturbation through serialization (e.g., saving to a file), as there are no continuous, in-memory representations like floating-point values that need rounding or clipping. As stated in the metric definition, methods that generate inputs directly in a serialized format, such as generated text, are considered to have high failure reproducibility.",
